# Day 2 - Timing Libraries, Synthesis Strategies and Flip-Flop Design

## Objective

The objective of Day 2 was to understand the role of timing libraries in digital design, explore different synthesis approaches, and study various flip-flop coding styles used in RTL design.

---

## Understanding the Liberty (.lib) File

One of the major topics covered during Day 2 was the study of the Liberty timing library file used during synthesis.

The Liberty (.lib) file contains information about standard cells available in the technology library. These cells are used by the synthesis tool to map RTL logic into actual hardware components.

### Observations

While exploring the library file, I observed that:

* Multiple versions of the same logic gate are available.
* Gates differ in speed, drive strength, area, and power consumption.
* Different implementations of gates allow the synthesis tool to select the most suitable cell based on design requirements.
* The library contains timing, functional, and electrical information required for technology mapping.

Examples include:

* 2-input AND gates
* 3-input AND gates
* 4-input AND gates
* Various inverter and buffer cells
* Sequential elements such as flip-flops

---

## Understanding Process, Voltage and Temperature (PVT)

I learned that the performance of an integrated circuit is influenced by three important factors:

### Process

Variations introduced during semiconductor fabrication.

### Voltage

Changes in supply voltage affect circuit speed and power consumption.

### Temperature

Temperature variations impact transistor characteristics and propagation delays.

These three parameters together are commonly referred to as **PVT corners**.

