## Hierarchical vs Flattened Synthesis

Another important concept studied during the lab was the difference between hierarchical and flattened synthesis.

### Hierarchical Synthesis

In hierarchical synthesis:

* Each module is synthesized separately.
* Module boundaries are preserved.
* The design structure remains organized.

### Observations

* Easier to analyze and debug.
* Individual modules can be studied independently.
* Useful for large designs with multiple blocks.

---

### Flattened Synthesis

In flattened synthesis:

* All modules are merged into a single design.
* Module hierarchy is removed.
* A unified netlist is generated.

### Observations

* Enables more aggressive optimization.
* Produces a single gate-level representation.
* Makes tracing individual modules more difficult.

---

## Comparison Performed

After observing both synthesis approaches, I noticed:

| Feature          | Hierarchical       | Flattened                  |
| ---------------- | ------------------ | -------------------------- |
| Module Structure | Preserved          | Removed                    |
| Readability      | Easier             | More complex               |
| Debugging        | Simpler            | Harder                     |
| Optimization     | Limited to modules | Entire design optimization |

The synthesized schematics clearly showed the difference between preserving module boundaries and combining the entire design into a single structure.

